         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0150">
               <p>Born of farming stock at <placeName>Malmerby</placeName> in
                     <placeName>Cumberland</placeName>, and educated by a Presbyterian minister,
                  Benson received a sound classical education. Converted under the influence of a
                  Methodist cousin, he was introduced to <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> and appointed classics master
                  at Kingswood School in <date when="1766">1766</date>, while still in his teens. In
                     <date when="1769">1769</date> Benson entered St. Edmund Hall,
                     <placeName>Oxford</placeName>, but was denied Anglican orders because of his
                  Methodist sympathies. After serving for a short time as headmaster of the
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0964.xml"/>Countess of
                     Huntingdon</persName>&apos;s ministerial training college at
                     <placeName>Trevecca</placeName>, he joined <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s Methodist <seg
                     ana="itinerancy">itinerancy</seg> in <date when="1771">1771</date>. In <date
                     when="1780">1780</date> he married <persName>Sarah Thompson</persName> in
                     <placeName>Leeds</placeName>. Benson was a great favorite of <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> and the two corresponded
                  often. He went on to become President of Conference in <date when="1798"
                     >1798</date> and <date when="1810">1810</date> and served as its secretary in
                     <date when="1805">1805</date> and <date when="1809">1809</date>. Throughout,
                  Benson was a staunch supporter of the link with the Church of England, and two of
                  his own sons entered the Anglican priesthood. See <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>,
                  84–85; Ives, <hi rend="italic">Kingswood</hi>, 64–71; <hi rend="italic"
                     >Minutes</hi> (post-Wesley, <date when="1821">1821</date>), 5:200–02; <hi
                     rend="italic">ODNB</hi>; and Vickers, <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>,
                  28.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
